3343 CONNECT 2 TWEET LINKEDIN 8 COMMENT EMAIL MORE EVANSTON, Ill. — Let’s just say it: This Iowa team might be pretty darn good.
The No. 17 Hawkeyes delivered yet another resilient performance Saturday, in the process collecting their second road win over a ranked opponent in 15 days and entrenching themselves at favorites in the Big Ten Conference’s West Division.
The final: Iowa 40, No. 20 Northwestern 10 — and Saturday’s next (next, next) man in was Akrum Wadley.
Wadley rushed for 204 yards, and his four touchdowns tied a school record, after starting running back Jordan Canzeri left the game in the first quarter with an ankle injury.
Wadley, who began the season fourth in Iowa’s running-back pecking order, was pressed into action after Canzeri’s left ankle got rolled on a tackle by Northwestern linebacker Jaylen Prater. Canzeri (who had 43 carries for 256 yards last week vs. Illinois) was taken to the locker room and returned to the Iowa sideline wearing a walking boot.
But Wadley was there to deliver his second breakthrough game — both coming against Northwestern.
HAWK CENTRAL
Iowa's Canzeri suffers ankle injury at Northwestern
Wadley rushed 15 times for 106 yards in last year’s 48-7 win over Northwestern, but has struggled to gain favor with his coaches due to ball-security concerns. Saturday, the 5-foot-11, 185-pound sophomore alleviated those quickly with a 6-yard run on his first carry. Then on the first play of the second quarter, he dashed around the left side for a 35-yard touchdown run and a 9-0 Iowa lead.
The Hawkeyes’ defense was stout yet again, as it was Oct. 3 in a 10-6 win at then-No. 19 Wisconsin. Now Iowa sits 7-0 overall, 3-0 in the Big Ten, with a bye this week before returning home Oct. 31 against Maryland.
C.J. Beathard, the subject of injury concerns all week, was limited by a sore right groin, but completed 15 of 25 passes for 176 yards. He was replaced by Tyler Wiegers in the fourth quarter with Iowa ahead 33-10.
